ir perspective on faith and abortion. They reflect on examples of faith organisations which have provided leadership on the issue as well as examining religious approaches from Buddhist, Christian, Jewish, Muslim and interfaith perspectives. Challenging the assumption that all people of faith are anti-abortion, this book provides a counterpoint to right-wing faith perspectives and outlines how faith communities reimagine abortion as an issue of social, pastoral and theological concern. Providing perspectives from the global North and South, it includes settings where abortion is legal, and where it is restricted, and settings where abortion stigma is ever-present to settings where abortion is normalised. It also demonstrates the complex connections between faith and abortion, how women and pregnant people are positioned in society and how morality is claimed and challenged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbortionxReligious aspects. 0aAbortion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Abortion & Birth Control.2bisacsh1 aAdibah, Syarifatul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloomer, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloomer, Fiona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLigomeka, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacNamara, Nóirín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalm, Selina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberto, María de los Ángeles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuttenberg, Rabbi Danya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurtle, Kellie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurtle, Kellie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov